Little's Law: The Mathematical Bridge

Little's Law is a fundamental queuing theory result that connects latency, throughput, and concurrency. Every software engineer who works on performance should know it:

L = λ × W

Where:
- L = average number of requests in the system at any given moment (concurrency)
- λ (lambda) = throughput (requests completed per unit time)
- W = average latency (time one request spends in the system)

Practical example:
Your API server handles 200 requests/second (λ = 200) and each request takes on average 100ms (W = 0.1s).

L = 200 × 0.1 = 20 concurrent requests in flight at any time.

This tells you how many threads, connections, or workers you need to sustain that performance. If your thread pool only has 10 threads, requests will queue up — which increases W, which increases L, which makes the queuing worse. This is how systems spiral into degradation under load.

Reverse application:
If you know your system has 50 concurrent connections (L = 50) and each request takes 200ms (W = 0.2s), then:
λ = L / W = 50 / 0.2 = 250 RPS is your throughput ceiling.

Want more throughput? Either add more concurrency (more threads/workers) or reduce latency per request. Little's Law shows you exactly which lever to pull.

