The Latency–Throughput Tradeoff

These two metrics often pull in opposite directions. Understanding when and why is a core engineering skill.

Batching: Throughput Up, Latency Up
Instead of writing each database record individually, you batch 500 records into one INSERT. Database throughput goes up dramatically — but any single record must wait for the batch to fill before it gets written. Latency for individual records increases.

This tradeoff appears everywhere: Kafka producers batch messages before sending, React batches DOM updates, GPUs batch matrix operations. Batching is a throughput optimization that trades away individual latency.

Caching: Latency Down, Throughput Up
A cache reduces the time to serve a request (lower latency) and simultaneously reduces load on the database (higher throughput for the overall system). Caching is one of the rare cases where both metrics improve together — at the cost of memory and consistency complexity.

Async Processing / Queues: Throughput Up, Latency Up
When a user submits a job, you put it in a queue and immediately return a 202 Accepted (fast acknowledgment). The job is processed asynchronously. The system can handle far more submissions per second (high throughput) but the actual completion of any one job may take much longer (high latency). Email sending, image processing, and report generation commonly use this pattern.

Connection Pooling: Throughput Up, Latency Down
Reusing database connections avoids the overhead of establishing a new TCP connection and auth handshake for every query. Both metrics improve — each query is faster (lower latency) and more queries can run per second (higher throughput).

Horizontal Scaling: Throughput Up, Latency Unchanged
Adding more servers allows you to handle more requests per second in aggregate (higher throughput). But any single request still takes the same time to process on its server (latency is unchanged unless the original server was overloaded).

