System Design Implications

When designing systems, latency and throughput constraints directly inform architectural decisions:

Database choice: Key-value stores like Redis have sub-millisecond latency but limited query throughput for complex workloads. Columnar databases like Redshift or BigQuery have high latency per query but enormous analytical throughput.

Synchronous vs. Asynchronous architecture: Synchronous systems (REST APIs) optimize for latency of individual calls. Asynchronous systems (event-driven, message queues) optimize for throughput and resilience.

Read replicas: Distributing reads across replicas increases read throughput but may introduce replication lag, which increases effective read latency for the freshest data.

CDNs: A content delivery network reduces latency by serving content from a node geographically close to the user. It also increases throughput of the origin server by offloading traffic.

Rate limiting: Intentionally caps throughput to protect downstream services from being overwhelmed. It sacrifices some throughput to guarantee latency stays within bounds for accepted requests.

