Bandwidth vs. Throughput (Don't Confuse These Either)

Bandwidth is the theoretical maximum capacity of a channel. Throughput is the actual rate achieved.

A 1 Gbps network interface card does not mean your application gets 1 Gbps. Protocol headers, TCP handshakes, retransmissions, serialization overhead, and application-level processing all reduce actual throughput below the theoretical bandwidth ceiling.

Always benchmark actual throughput — don't assume bandwidth equals throughput.

