Common Misconceptions

"If the server CPU is low, latency must be fine" — Wrong. Latency can be high due to network round trips, database wait time, lock contention, or queuing — none of which show up as CPU usage.

"Scaling horizontally will fix our slow responses" — Not if the bottleneck is a single slow database query. Adding servers multiplies throughput capacity but doesn't fix a poorly indexed query that takes 2 seconds.

"Our average response time is 80ms, so we're good" — Check your P99. If 1% of requests take 3 seconds, you have a real problem that averages are hiding.

"High throughput means the system is healthy" — A system can be processing thousands of requests per second but all of them are returning errors. Throughput of successful operations is what matters.

"Latency and response time are the same thing" — Response time = latency of processing + time spent waiting in queue. Under load, a request may wait 500ms in a queue before any processing even begins. That queuing time is invisible to your processing latency metric but very visible to your user.

